  "prompt": "What is the difference between centripetal force and centrifugal force?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the key differences between centripetal and centrifugal forces:\n\nCentripetal Force:\n1. Real, actual force\n2. Points toward the center of circular motion\n3. Causes an object to move in a circular path\n4. Provided by an external agent (like tension, gravity, friction)\n5. Always directed inward\n6. Required to maintain circular motion\n7. Exists in the reference frame of the rotating object\n\nCentrifugal Force:\n1. Apparent/fictitious force\n2. Points away from the center of circular motion\n3. Perceived by an observer in a rotating reference frame\n4. Not a real physical force\n5. Always directed outward\n6. Experienced as a sensation of being pushed away from the center\n7. Exists only in the rotating reference frame\n\nExample:\nIn a roller coaster loop, the actual force keeping the car on the track is the centripetal force (provided by the track). The sensation of being pushed outward is the perceived centrifugal force.\n\nIn summary, centripetal force is a real force causing circular motion, while centrifugal force is an apparent force experienced in a rotating reference frame.",
